06275nam a22005895i 9780520931527DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209315277 a10.1525/97805209315272doi  a(DE-B1597)521073  a(OCoLC)56025156  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aG69.B75bS65 2003 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a304.209730904a910.92Ba910/.921 aSmith, Neil, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Empire :bRoosevelt's Geographer and the Prelude to Globalization /cNeil Smith. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (584 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Critical Human Geography ;v900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Maps -- tPrologue -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Lost Geography of the American Century -- t2. 1898 and the Making of a Practical Man -- t3. "Conditional Conquest": Geography, Labor, and Exploration in South America -- t4. The Search for Geographical Order: The American Geographical Society -- t5. The Inquiry: Geography and a "Scientific Peace" -- t6. A Last Hurrah for Old World Geographies: Fixing Space at the Paris Peace Conference -- t7. "Revolutionarily Yours": The New World, the Council on Foreign Relations, and the Making of Liberal Foreign Policy -- t8. "The Geography of Internal Affairs": Pioneer Settlement as National Economic Development -- t9. The Kantian University: Science and Nation Building at Johns Hopkins -- t10. Geopolitics: The Reassertion of Old World Geographies -- t11. Silence and Refusal: Refugees, Race, and Economic Development -- t12. Settling Affairs with the Old World: Dismembering Germany? -- t13. Toward Development: Shaking Loose the Colonies -- t14. Frustrated Globalism, Compromise Geographies: Designing the United Nations -- t15. Defeat from the Jaws of Victory -- t16. Geographical Solicitude,Vital Anomaly -- tCollections Consulted -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn American Empire, constructed over the last century, long ago overtook European colonialism, and it has been widely assumed that the new globalism it espoused took us "beyond geography." Neil Smith debunks that assumption, offering an incisive argument that American globalism had a distinct geography and was pieced together as part of a powerful geographical vision. The power of geography did not die with the twilight of European colonialism, but it did change fundamentally. That the inauguration of the American Century brought a loss of public geographical sensibility in the United States was itself a political symptom of the emerging empire. This book provides a vital geographical-historical context for understanding the power and limits of contemporary globalization, which can now be seen as representing the third of three distinct historical moments of U.S. global ambition.The story unfolds through a decisive account of the career of Isaiah Bowman (1878-1950), the most famous American geographer of the twentieth century. For nearly four decades Bowman operated around the vortex of state power, working to bring an American order to the global landscape. An explorer on the famous Machu Picchu expedition of 1911 who came to be known first as "Woodrow Wilson's geographer," and later as Frankin D. Roosevelt's, Bowman was present at the creation of U.S. liberal foreign policy. A quarter-century later, Bowman was at the center of Roosevelt's State Department, concerned with the disposition of Germany and heightened U.S. access to European colonies; he was described by Dean Acheson as a key "architect of the United Nations." In that period he was a leader in American science, served as president of Johns Hopkins University, and became an early and vociferous cold warrior. A complicated, contradictory, and at times controversial figure who was very much in the public eye, he appeared on the cover of Time magazine. Bowman's career as a geographer in an era when the value of geography was deeply questioned provides a unique window into the contradictory uses of geographical knowledge in the construction of the American Empire. Smith's historical excavation reveals, in broad strokes yet with lively detail, that today's American-inspired globalization springs not from the 1980s but from two earlier moments in 1919 and 1945, both of which ended in failure. By recharting the geography of this history, Smith brings the politics-and the limits-of contemporary globalization sharply into focus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aGeographersxBiographyxUnited States. 0aGeographerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aGeographyxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aGeographyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGlobalizationxHistoryx20th century. 0aGlobalizationxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520931527423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520931527.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles